    Top reviews from the United States

    M. C. Yu
    4.0 out of 5 stars Still one of the best value ergo keyboards, not as nice as the older production MS Natural 4000.
    Reviewed in the United States on February 24, 2023
    Verified Purchase
    I put off replacing my last MS Natural 4000 for as long as I could, but all electronics do eventually die... I bought this one for myself at the beginning of 2023, and one for my wife a few years ago. Overall, the key action is nice and quick, and soft sounding. You can tell they're squishy rubber dome spring thingies underneath the keys. No annoying clacky sounds like my son loves on his mega bright rainbow keyboard that he plays Fortnite on and can't quite hit 20wpm. This one does just fine smashing 90-100wpm.

    The extra function keys at the top don't all work through my KVM (not expected to), but the upper right section does. I'm not used to using them yet, but being able to trigger Win 10's screenshot function, task switcher, and screen lock from dedicated buttons at the top is nice. The separate search button works too. Audio controls don't work through KVM. The quick launch 1-2-3 (takes the first 3 items in your task bar quick launch section) buttons DO work. The KVM I'm referring to is the TESmart brand, item number B0867BPPFQ, which I think is one of the KVM values, and with the keyboard plugged into the limited keyboard port and not the shared USB port.

    Other things I like vs the old MS Natural 4000: no need for a function lock key to access your F1-F12 buttons. Function row is dedicated and has no secondary function. No left/right button set below the space bar to constantly hit.

    Things I DON'T like vs the MS Natural 4000: The function row is laid in right on top of your number row, so the buttons aren't as easy to find purely by feel, and sometimes I get messed up between hitting normal numbers and F numbers. The NumLock key isn't on the top left of the number pad, it's replaced by the '=' equals button instead. Odd substitution. The Caps lock key has no indicator. I realize that you'll figure it out as soon as you start typing, but passwords can get hosed without you knowing it. I think this is the biggest problem with the keyboard, to be honest.

    The last issue I have is with the riser. I actually liked the high riser on the 4000 that picked up the front edge of the keyboard higher than the rear. The keyboard leaning back like the 4000 is actually better for wrist positioning, since it allows your fingers to hang down as opposed to be pointed up from the wrist pad. I'll have to add a wedge under this keyboard to bring the front up a bit.

    Overall this is a good successor (is it according to MS? not sure) to the MS Natural 4000 series that I used for over a decade, especially when the price dips down to $40 or below. I'll probably keep buying this model until MS redesigns again.

    Top reviews from other countries

    Sean Murphy
    3.0 out of 5 stars A Solid "B" Effort; but the 4000 is Better
    Reviewed in Canada on September 3, 2020
    Verified Purchase
    So I've read a lot of the reviews on this keyboard, looked at the Logitech competition, tried without success to find a 4000 to replace my broken one; and ended up ordering this one anyways.

    The Good:
    - It's better than a standard keyboard; I've been typing on MS Ergonomic keyboards since 1995 because my Dad has arthritis and was told by his doctor to try this out. He replaced our family keyboard and told the rest of us to deal with it. 25 years later; it's all my family uses
    - It wasn't terribly expensive. It's not a $20 toss in keyboard from Dell; nor is it a $200 Logitech ergonomic keyboard (that still doesn't have backlight / mechanical / anything really fancy besides their wifi features I don't care for or need).
    - It came quickly from Amazon as expected
    - It was under $100
    - It still has positive lift in the front; which after getting it with the Wireless Desktop and then 4000, I can't live without

    The Bad
    - The key location changes (moving delete, print screen, the menu key (which no one uses ever), were pointless. A wider ALT key would've been preferred
    - It has no backlighting, I don't need this as I'm a 100% touch typist, but people seem to like it
    - Mechanical Keys / RGB would be sweet; but I know that's not Microsoft's thing.

    The Ugly
    - The wider layout mimics the sculpt keyboard, and probably uses similar moldings at the factory; but I prefer the tighter 4000 layout
    - Microsoft got rid of the 4000 wired for no real reason
    - It still doesn't have great Mac support; thankfully 3rd party apps help make most of the feature keys usable

    ** Bottom line from a IT guy who's been typing on Microsoft Ergonomic keyboards for 25 years and probably used every model there is in the lineup: **

    Its not the 4000, it changes the key layout unnecessarily; it will take some adjustment; however if you want an ergonomic keyboard; and don't want the laptop style keys of the Sculpt or the "gets dirty instantly" like the fabric on the Surface keyboard - this is basically your only option.

    Not perfect, but it's all we've got without eBay hunting for used options (gross).

    NJ
    3.0 out of 5 stars 100% not for 10 fingered typer.
    Reviewed in Canada on January 17, 2022
    Verified Purchase
    I miss the older style Microsoft ergonomic. I'm such a fast and accurate 10 finger typer. I've been using this keyboard for a couple weeks now and some of the buttons are off their usual spots. The backspace and delete button upper right is so awkwardly near each other and throws me off repeatedly. The rise in the middle of the keyboard is too tall. I'm in need of F3 and Y together in my job for a lot of the day. Believe me when I say that this function is now impossible ergonomically. I find myself looking at the keyboard more than I used to, and my accuracy has declined. I've never had this happen with any keyboard before. I also dislike that the wrist rest has been rounded off and shortened at the number pad. It should have been the same all the way across. The makes me the most upset about this keyboard as I live on the 10-key number pad all day.
    A couple of pros, the emoji button is fun in Teams, the space bar is nice and big, the fact that it's USB plug-in is incredibly helpful, this keyboard is as wide as I wanted it at 19", like the old model, and the wrist rest is actually super comfortable but also can be wiped down.
    I do have to say that I spilled a half cup of water right on the keyboard. I poured the water out of it, dried up with paper towel as best I could, and it still works like a charm. I picked out one of the keys with a key picker to soak up some of the excess water and I like how under the keys is flat so the keys actually hide the mechanical parts. The design did save me when I mistaking knocked the cup of water over in to the keys.

    All in all, I will be shopping for a new keyboard and this will go in to storage maybe next year.
    I need Microsoft to make a backlit version of their old style ergonomic, so the keys are lit up too. That's my ultimate goal keyboard...proper ergonomic, 19" wide with no unnecessary keys at the top, backlit including the key characters being lit. I was hoping this keyboard would take away my want for the ergonomic backlit since they're hard to find or so incredibly expensive, but the function of it is just poor for 10 finger typers.
